{"title_page": "Ariffin Omar", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Senator]] \n| name = Ariffin Omar\n| honorific-suffix = [[Dewan Negara|MP]]\n| image =Arrifin omar.png\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| office = Senator for [[Penang]] in the [[Dewan Negara|Malaysian Parliament]]\n| term_start = 2 June 2015\n| term_end = 2 June 2018\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| office2 = Vice-chairman of [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP)\n| term_start2 = 16 December 2012\n| term_end2 = \n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 =\n| party = [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) \n| otherparty = [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH)\n| religion = [[Islam]]\n| occupation = Politician, Lecturer \n| alma_mater= [[University of Science Malaysia]] (USM) <br> [[National University of Singapore]] (NUS) <br> [[Australia National University]] (ANU)\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1949}}\n| birth_place = [[Penang]], [[Malaysia]]\n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| relations =\n| spouse =\n| children = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Ariffin S.M Omar''' is a [[Malaysia]]n politician who is a Vice Chairman of the [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP), a component party of [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) coalition. He served as a [[senator]] elected by the [[Penang State Legislative Assembly]] in the [[Dewan Negara|Parliament of Malaysia]] from 2 June 2015 to 2 June 2018\n\n== Personal life and education ==\nAriffin Omar studied at St Xavier's Institution, [[Penang]] for his secondary school education. He then continued to study at [[Universiti Sains Malaysia]] (USM) and later obtained a [[Bachelor's degree]] at the [[National University of Singapore]] (NUS) and in 1990, obtained a [[Doctorate degree]] from the [[Australia National University]] (ANU).<ref name=\"gb\">{{cite web | url=http://gbgerakbudaya.com/bookshop/index.php?main_page=product_book_info&products_id=2574 | title=gerak budaya | accessdate=8 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe worked as a lecturer in [[Universiti Sains Malaysia]] (1974\u20132006) and a lecturer at the [[University of Utah]] (1998) and was also a lecturer in  [[Universiti Utara Malaysia]] and the [[National Defence University of Malaysia]].<ref name=\"gb\"/>\n\nHe was also a founding member of [[Aliran Kesedaran Negara]] (Aliran), a reform movement dedicated to justice, freedom and solidarity.<ref name=\"gb\"/>\n\nNow based at the Penang Institute, his research focuses on nation, nationalism, ethnic relations and religious freedom.<ref name=\"gb\"/>\n\n== Works ==\n*Bangsa Melayu (Malay Concepts of Democracy and Community, 1945\u20131950) ; Oxford University Press, 1993\n*The Bumiputera Policy: Dynamics and Dilemmas ;  Penerbit Universiti Sains Malaysia, 2005\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Omar, Ariffin}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Democratic Action Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n\n\n{{Malaysia-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Politician\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Senator]] \n| name = Ariffin Omar\n| honorific-suffix = [[Dewan Negara|MP]]\n| image =Arrifin omar.png\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| office = Senator for [[Penang]] in the [[Dewan Negara|Malaysian Parliament]]\n| term_start = 2 June 2015\n| term_end = 2 June 2018\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| office2 = Vice-chairman of [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP)\n| term_start2 = 16 December 2012\n| term_end2 = \n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 =\n| party = [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP) \n| otherparty = [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH)\n| religion = [[Islam]]\n| occupation = Politician, Lecturer \n| alma_mater= [[University of Science Malaysia]] (USM) <br> [[National University of Singapore]] (NUS) <br> [[Australia National University]] (ANU)\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1949}}\n| birth_place = [[Penang]], [[Malaysia]]\n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| relations =\n| spouse =\n| children = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Ariffin S.M Omar''' is a [[Malaysia]]n politician who is a Vice Chairman of the [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP), a component party of [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) coalition. He served as a [[senator]] elected by the [[Penang State Legislative Assembly]] in the [[Dewan Negara|Parliament of Malaysia]] from 2 June 2015 to 2 June 2018\n\n== Personal life and education ==\nAriffin Omar studied at St Xavier's Institution, [[Penang]] for his secondary school education. He then continued to study at [[Universiti Sains Malaysia]] (USM) and later obtained a [[Bachelor's degree]] at the [[National University of Singapore]] (NUS) and in 1990, obtained a [[Doctorate degree]] from the [[Australia National University]] (ANU).<ref name=\"gb\">{{cite web | url=http://gbgerakbudaya.com/bookshop/index.php?main_page=product_book_info&products_id=2574 | title=gerak budaya | accessdate=8 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe worked as a lecturer in [[Universiti Sains Malaysia]] (1974\u20132006) and a lecturer at the [[University of Utah]] (1998) and was also a lecturer in  [[Universiti Utara Malaysia]] and the [[National Defence University of Malaysia]].<ref name=\"gb\"/>\n\nHe was also a founding member of [[Aliran Kesedaran Negara]] (Aliran), a reform movement dedicated to justice, freedom and solidarity.<ref name=\"gb\"/>\n\nNow based at the Penang Institute, his research focuses on nation, nationalism, ethnic relations and religious freedom.<ref name=\"gb\"/>\n\n== Works ==\n*Bangsa Melayu (Malay Concepts of Democracy and Community, 1945\u20131950) ; Oxford University Press, 1993\n*The Bumiputera Policy: Dynamics and Dilemmas ;  Penerbit Universiti Sains Malaysia, 2005\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Omar, Ariffin}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Democratic Action Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n\n\n{{Malaysia-politician-stub}}\n{{malaysia-bio-stub}}\n{{politics-stub}}\n{{malaysia-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "stub sorting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ariffin_Omar"}
{"title_page": "Noraini Ahmad", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Malay name|Noraini|Ahmad}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Dato'|Dato']] [[Dr.]]\n| name = Noraini Ahmad\n| native_name = \u0646\u0648\u0631\u0639\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0628\u0646\u062a \u0623\u062d\u0645\u062f\n| honorific-suffix = {{small|[[Orders, decorations, and medals of Pahang|DSAP]] [[List of post-nominal letters (Malacca)|DMSM]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]]}}\n| image = Noraini Ahmad.jpg\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Noraini binti Ahmad\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1967|11|07|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Kampung Bintang, Peserai Parit Sulong, [[Johor]]\n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| office = [[Minister of Education (Malaysia)|Minister of Higher Education]]\n| term_end = \n| term_start = 10 March 2020\n| primeminister = [[Muhyiddin Yassin]]\n| deputy = [[Mansor Othman]]\n| constituency = [[Parit Sulong (federal constituency)|Parit Sulong]]\n| monarch = [[Abdullah of Pahang|Abdullah]]\n| predecessor = [[Mahathir Mohamad]] {{small|as Acting Minister of Education}}\n| successor = \n| office2 = [[Ministry of Human Resources (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Human Resources]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Abdullah Ahmad Badawi]]\n| term_end2 = 9 April 2009\n| term_start2 = 19 March 2008\n| constituency2 = [[Parit Sulong (federal constituency)|Parit Sulong]]\n| minister2 = [[Subramaniam Sathasivam]]\n| monarch2 = [[Mizan Zainal Abidin of Terengganu|Mizan Zainal Abidin]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Abdul Rahman Bakar]]\n| successor2 = [[Maznah Mazlan]]\n| constituency_MP4 = [[Parit Sulong (federal constituency)|Parit Sulong]]\n| parliament4 = Malaysian\n| term_start4 = 2008\n| term_end4 =\n| majority4 = 13,599 [[2008 Malaysian general election|(2008)]]<br/>11,753 [[2013 Malaysian general election|(2013)]]<br/>6,341 [[2018 Malaysian general election|(2018)]]\n| predecessor4 = Syed Hood Syed Edros ([[United Malay National Organisation|UMNO]]\u2014[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor4 =\n| office1 = Women Chief of [[United Malay National Organisation]]\n| president1 = [[Ahmad Zahid Hamidi]]<br />[[Mohamad Hasan (politician)|Mohamad Hasan]] (''Acting'')\n| term_start1 = 25 June 2018\n| term_end1 =   \n| predecessor1 = [[Shahrizat Abdul Jalil]]\n| successor1 = \n| deputy1 = [[Norliza Rahim]]\n| constituency1 = [[Parit Sulong (federal constituency)|Parit Sulong]]\n| office3 = Chairperson of [[Public Accounts Committee (Malaysia)]]\n| term_start3 = 11 April 2019\n| predecessor3 = [[Ronald Kiandee]]\n| nominator3 = [[Mahathir Mohamad]]\n| deputy3 = [[Wong Kah Woh]]\n| appointer3 = [[Mohamad Ariff Md Yusof]]\n| term_end3 = \n| party = [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO)\n| otherparty = [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN)\n| occupation = [[Politician]]\n| relations =\n| spouse =\n| children = 2\n| alma_mater = [[University of Saskatchewan]]\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n[[Malay titles#Dato'|Dato']] [[Dr.]] '''Noraini binti Ahmad''' ([[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u0646\u0648\u0631\u0639\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0628\u0646\u062a \u0623\u062d\u0645\u062f; born 7 November 1967) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] [[politician]] from the [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO) in [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) coalition currently serving as three-term [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) of [[Parliament of Malaysia|Malaysia]] for the [[Parit Sulong (federal constituency)|Parit Sulong]] constituency in the state of [[Johor]] and chairperson of the [[Public Accounts Committee (Malaysia)|Public Accounts Committee]] (PAC).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/04/11/parit-sulong-mp-dr-noraini-ahmad-is-new-pac-chairman-after-voice-vote/|accessdate=11 April 2019|date=11 April 2019|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)]]|title=Parit Sulong MP Dr Noraini Ahmad is new PAC chairman after voice vote|work=Martin Carvalho, Hemananthani Sivanandam, Rahimy Rahim, and Tarrence Tan}}</ref> She is the current chairperson of the women's wing of UMNO (Wanita UMNO), since June 2018, and also currently serving as Minister of Higher Education since 10 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/politics/2018/06/382893/noraini-aims-bring-renewal-wanita-umno|title=Noraini aims to bring renewal to Wanita Umno|date=22 June 2018|work=New Straits Times|accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref> She was also the head of UMNO's women's youth wing (Puteri UMNO) from 2004 to 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sinarharian.com.my/politik/puteri-beri-anugerah-khas-kepada-bekas-ketua-1.227245|title=Puteri beri anugerah khas kepada bekas ketua|date=4 December 2013|work=Sinar Harian|accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nNoraini was first elected to federal Parliament in the [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008 general election]], replacing incumbent Syed Hood Syed Edros. Immediately after the election, she was named [[Ministry of Human Resources (Malaysia)|Deputy Minister of Human Resources]] in the government of [[Abdullah Ahmad Badawi]] and served under the post until Abdullah's successor [[Najib Razak]] named his first cabinet in April 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2008/03/19/new-ministers-and-deputy-ministers/|title=New ministers and deputy ministers|date=19 March 2008|work=The Star|accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2013 Malaysian general election|2013 general election]], Noraini won re-election to Parliament and was then appointed by the government as the chairperson of the Malaysia External Trade Development Corporation (Matrade).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesundaily.my/news/843586|title=Noraini Ahmad is new Matrade chairman|date=30 September 2013|work=The Sun|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref> In the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 general election]], Noraini was re-elected once again albeit with a decreased majority.\n\nNoraini is also the current chairman of [[Commonwealth Parliamentary Association#Officers|Commonwealth Women Parliamentarians]], since December 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/politics/2018/06/382893/noraini-aims-bring-renewal-wanita-umno|title=Noraini Ahmad elected as CWP Chairman|date=17 December 2016|work=New Straits Times|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref> The Commonwealth Women Parliamentarians (CWP) is a network of the [[Commonwealth Parliamentary Association]] that campaigns for gender equality and equal representation in Parliaments.\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]''': P147 [[Parit Sulong (federal constituency)|Parit Sulong]], Johor<ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=6 June 2010 }} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{Cite web\n  | title = Malaysia General Election \n  | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data\n  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]\n  | url = http://undi.info/\n  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref><ref name=\"GE13 results\">{{cite web|url=http://resultpru13.spr.gov.my/module/keputusan/paparan/paparan_laporan.php|title=KEPUTUSAN PILIHAN RAYA UMUM 13|work=Sistem Pengurusan Maklumat Pilihan Raya Umum|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref name =\"myundi pru 13\">{{cite web |url=http://www.myundi.com.my/pru13/region.aspx |title=my undi : Kawasan & Calon-Calon PRU13 : Keputusan PRU13 (Archived copy) |website=www.myundi.com.my|accessdate=2014-04-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331000718/http://www.myundi.com.my/pru13/region.aspx |archivedate=