Aik}}\n* {{twitter|@nweiaik}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ng, Wei Aik}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Malaysian politicians of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Democratic Action Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{Malaysia-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Chinese name|[[Huang (surname)|Ng]] ({{noitalic|{{linktext|\u9ec4|lang=zh-hans}}}})}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image = \n|imagesize =\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Ng Wei Aik\n| native_name = {{nobold|{{lang|zh-hans|\u9ec4\u4f1f\u76ca}}}}\n| honorific-suffix = \n| constituency_MP2 = [[Tanjong (federal constituency)|Tanjong]]\n| parliament2       = Malaysian\n| term_start2       = 5 March 2013\n| term_end2         = 9 May 2018\n| majority2         = 28,645 ([[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]])\n| predecessor2      = [[Chow Kon Yeow]] ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]-[[Pakatan Rakyat|PR]])\n| successor2        = [[Chow Kon Yeow]] ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]-[[Pakatan Harapan|PH]])\n| assembly3        = Penang State\n| constituency_AM3 = [[Komtar (state constituency)|Komtar]]\n| term_start3      =  8 March 2008 \n| term_end3        = 5 March 2013\n| majority3        =  3.328 ([[2008 Malaysian general election|2008]])\n| predecessor3     = Lim Gim Soon ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]]-[[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n| successor3       = Teh Lai Heng ([[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]-[[Pakatan Rakyat|PR]])\n| birth_name = Ng Wei Aik\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|12|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[George Town, Penang|George Town]], [[Penang]], Malaysia\n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| party = [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP)\n| otherparty = [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH)\n| religion = \n| parents =\n| occupation = Politician\n| alma_mater = [[University of Malaya]]\n| children = \n| website = {{URL|http://ngweiaik.com}}\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Ng Wei Aik''' ({{zh|s=\u9ec4\u4f1f\u76ca|zh|t=\u9ec3\u5049\u76ca|p=Hu\u00e1ng W\u011biy\u00ec}}; born 20 December 1977) is a [[Malaysians|Malaysian]] politician of [[Malaysian Chinese|Chinese]] origin. He is the former \n[[Dewan Rakyat|Member of Parliament]] for [[Tanjong (federal constituency)|Tanjong]] parliamentary constituency for one term from 2013 to 2018, representing [[Democratic Action Party]] (DAP), a component of [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) coalition.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ngweiaik.com/# | title=Ng Wei Aik | publisher=DAPMalaysia | accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.parlimen.gov.my/ahli-dewan.html?uweb=dr | title=Member of Parliaments | publisher=Official Portal of Malaysian Parliament | accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nNg was also the [[Penang State Legislative Assembly|Penang State Assemblyman]] of [[Komtar]] seat for one term from 2008 to 2013.\n\nNg was dropped by DAP as a candidate in the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 general election]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/04/21/penang-dap-leaders-make-way-party-to-announce-new-candidates-today-in-sweeping-changes/ | title=DAP six face the axe | publisher= [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|date=21 April 2018|author= K. Suthakar and Arnold Loh|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe was also the former political secretary of [[Lim Guan Eng]], chief minister of Penang but he resigned the post in March 2014 to focus on his job as member of parliament.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chinanews.com/hr/2014/03-04/5906152.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5411\u6765\u6562\u6012\u6562\u8a00 \u9ec4\u4f1f\u76ca\u8f9e\u5927\u9a6c\u69df\u5dde\u9996\u957f\u653f\u6cbb\u79d8\u4e66\u804c\u4f4d | publisher=China News |date=| language = zh-hans | accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref>\n \nNg is an alumnus of [[University of Malaya]] (UM) and [[Chung Ling High School]].\n\n==Election results==