mocratic Action Party}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Ng Wei Aik'''}} ('''[[Democratic Action Party|DAP]]''')\n|align=\"right\" |'''35,510'''\n|'''83.80%'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Ng Song Kheng ([[Parti Gerakan Rakyat Malaysia|Gerakan]])\n|align=\"right\" |6,865\n|16.20%\n|42,903\n|28,645\n|83.33%\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{facebook|NgWeiAik}}\n* {{twitter|@nweiaik}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ng, Wei Aik}}\n[[Category:Malaysian politicians of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Democratic Action Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{Malaysia-politician-stub}}\n{{malaysia-bio-stub}}\n{{politics-stub}}\n{{malaysia-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:stub sorting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ng_Wei_Aik"}
{"title_page": "Pandikar Amin Mulia", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Malay name|Pandikar Amin|Mulia}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berbahagia]] [[Malay titles#Tan Sri|Tan Sri]] [[Malay titles#Datuk Seri|Datuk Seri Panglima]]\n| honorific-suffix = {{small|[[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia|PSM]] [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the Malaysian states and federal territories#Federal Territories|SUMW]] [[List of post-nominal letters (Penang)|DUPN]] [[Order of Kinabalu|SPDK]]}}\n| name             = Pandikar Amin Mulia\n| native_name      = \u06a4\u0646\u062f\u0643\u0627\u0631 \u0623\u0645\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u0644\u064a\u0627\n| image            = Amin Mulia at the Former Parliament of Iran Building 24.08.2016.jpg\n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Pandikar Amin bin Mulia\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1955|09|17|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Kota Belud]], [[Crown Colony of North Borneo]] (now [[Sabah]], [[Malaysia]])\n| residence        =\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n\n| office1          = 8th [[Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n| parliament1      = Malaysian\n| term_start1      = 28 April 2008\n| term_end1        = 10 May 2018\n| predecessor1     = [[Ramli Ngah Talib]]\n| successor1       = [[Mohamad Ariff Md Yusof]]\n| monarch1 = [[Mizan Zainal Abidin of Terengganu|Mizan Zainal Abidin]]<br />[[Abdul Halim of Kedah|Abdul Halim]]<br />[[Muhammad V of Kelantan|Muhammad V]]\n| primeminister1   = [[Abdullah Ahmad Badawi]]<br />[[Najib Razak]]\n| constituency1    = ''non-MP'' ([[Barisan Nasional]])\n\n| office2 = [[Minister in the Prime Minister's Department]]\n| term_start2 = 15 December 1999\n| term_end2 = 1 July 2003\n| primeminister2 = [[Mahathir Mohamad]]\n| monarch2 = [[Salahuddin of Selangor|Salahuddin]]<br />[[Sirajuddin of Perlis|Sirajuddin]]\n| constituency2 = ''Senator''\n\n| constituency_AM3 = [[Tempasuk (state constituency)|Tempasuk]]\n| assembly3 = Sabah State Legislative\n| term_start3 = 2004\n| term_end3 = 2008\n| predecessor3 = Musbah Jamli\n| successor3 = Musbah Jamli\n\n| constituency_AM4 = [[Usukan (state constituency)|Usukan]]\n| assembly4 = Sabah State Legislative\n| term_start4 = 1982\n| term_end4 = 1985\n| predecessor4 = [[Mohamed Said Keruak]]\n| successor4 = [[Mustapha Harun]]\n\n| office5          = President of [[People's Justice Front]] (AKAR)\n| term_start5      = 1989\n| term_end5        = 1995\n| predecessor5     = ''Inaugural holder''\n| successor5       = ''Post abolished''\n\n| citizenship      = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| party            = [[Independent politician|Independent]] (2019-)<br />[[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO) (2001-2018)<br />[[People's Justice Front]] (AKAR) (1989-2001)<br />[[United Sabah National Organisation]] (USNO) (1986-1989)\n| otherparty       = [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) (1986-2018)\n| occupation       = [[Politician]]\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Wolverhampton]]<br />[[Lincoln's Inn]]\n| relations        =\n| spouse           = Hadijah Abdullah Teng\n| children         =\n| website          =\n| footnotes        =\n}}\n\n[[Malay titles#Tan Sri|Tan Sri]] [[Malay titles#Datuk Seri|Datuk Seri Panglima]] '''Pandikar Amin bin Mulia''' ([[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u06a4\u0646\u062f\u0643\u0627\u0631 \u0623\u0645\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u0644\u064a\u0627; born 17 September 1955) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician. He was the [[Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat|Speaker]] of the [[Dewan Rakyat]], the lower house of the [[Parliament of Malaysia]] from April 2008 to May 2018. Presently he is an [[independent politician]].\n\n== Early background ==\nPandikar Amin was born in a poor family in a remote village in [[Kota Belud]], [[Sabah]]. Prior to going to [[England]] for tertiary education, he received education at [[Maktab Sabah, Kota Kinabalu|Sabah College]] in [[Kota Kinabalu]]. He was a graduate of [[University of Wolverhampton|Wolverhampton Polytechnic]] and [[Lincoln's Inn]].\n\n== Political career ==\n=== Pre-speakership ===\nPandikar Amin entered politics in 1982 as a member of [[United Sabah National Organisation]] (USNO) and later picked as the [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) parliamentary candidate for [[Kota Belud (federal constituency)|Kota Belud]] in [[1982 Malaysian general election|1982 general elections]] but lost to the Independent candidate. At the age of 27, however he became [[Sabah State Legislative Assembly|Sabah state assemblyman]] for [[Usukan (state constituency)|Usukan]] from 1982 to 1985. He was appointed the Speaker of [[Sabah State Legislative Assembly]] from 1986 to 1988.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2008/5/1/parliament/21119683&sec=parliament|title=Baptism of fire for Speaker Pandikar Amin at first sitting|date=1 May 2008|work=The Star|accessdate=1 May 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501130318/http://www.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2008%2F5%2F1%2Fparliament%2F21119683&sec=parliament|archivedate=1 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, he was appointed as a [[Dewan Negara|Senator]] and Minister in the [[Prime Minister's Department (Malaysia)|Prime Minister's Department]] until 2002. He was president of [[People's Justice Front]] (AKAR), one of the BN component parties in [[Sabah]], at that time. He was elected again Sabah assemblyman from 2004 to 2008; for [[Tempasuk (state constituency)|Tempasuk]].\n\n=== Speakership in the Dewan Rakyat ===\nAfter the [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008 general elections]], the BN coalition government announced that Pandikar, a member of the [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO), would be the new Speaker, replacing [[Ramli Ngah Talib]].<ref>{{cite news| title=MPs urged to follow the rules| date=26 April 2008| url=http://themalaysianinsider.com/mni/mps-urged-to-follow-the-rules.html| work=The Malaysian Insider| accessdate=27 April 2008| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717012931/http://themalaysianinsider.com/mni/mps-urged-to-follow-the-rules.html| archivedate=17 July 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe 12th Parliament was the first to be presided over entirely by East Malaysians; Pandikar and his deputies, [[Wan Junaidi Tuanku Jaafar]] and [[Ronald Kiandee]], hail from either [[Sabah]] or [[Sarawak]].<ref>{{cite news | first=V. | last=Vasudevan | author2= | title=A day of firsts in parliament | date=28 April 2008 | publisher= | url =http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Monday/National/2225389/Article/index_html | work =[[New Straits Times]] | pages = | accessdate = 28 April 2008 | language = |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080501173244/http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Monday/National/2225389/Article/index_html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 1 May 2008}}</ref> In mid-May, after Parliament convened, Pandikar resigned as Kota Marudu UMNO division chief, citing the need to be a neutral presiding officer. He denied his resignation was linked to possible party-switching amongst UMNO MPs from East Malaysia.<ref>{{cite news | title=Pandikar Amin quits as Kota Marudu Umno chief | date=16 May 2008 | publisher= | url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2008/05/16/pandikar-amin-quits-as-kota-marudu-umno-chief/ | work=[[The Star Online]] | accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nAhead of the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 general elections]], Pandikar announced his intention to contest, thus returning to active politics after serving as Parliamentary Speaker for two terms.<ref>{{cite news | first=Clarence | last=Dol | title=Pandikar returning to politics | date=5 April 2017 | url=http://dailyexpress.com.my/news.cfm?NewsID=116899 | work=Daily Express | accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref> Somehow he was not pick as candidate to contest the elections that saw the downfall of BN in both the federal and state governments. Amidst his appointment to the UMNO's supreme council in 14 July 2018; he quitted on 12 December 2018 along with other Sabah UMNO assemblyman to be independents.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2018/12/13/umno-sabah-ship-sinking/|title=Umno Sabah ship sinking|author=NEIL BRIAN JOSEPH|publisher=[[The Borneo Post]]|date=13 December 2018|accessdate=13 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* {{Flag|Malaysia}} :\n** [[File:Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia - SSM.svg|50px]] Companion of the [[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia#Companion|Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia]] (JSM) (1993)\n** [[File:Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia - PSM.svg|50px]] Commander of the [[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia#Commander|Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia]] (PSM) - '''Tan Sri''' (2002)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.istiadat.gov.my/index.php/component/semakanlantikanskp/|title=Semakan Penerima Darjah Kebesaran, Bintang dan Pingat}}</ref>\n\n* {{Flag|Federal Territory (Malaysia)}} :\n** [[File:MY-FED Darjah Mahkota Wilayah - Grand Knight - SUMW.svg|50px]] Grand Knight of the [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the Malaysian states and federal territories#Federal Territories|Order of the Territorial Crown]] (SUMW) - '''Datuk Seri Utama''' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2009/02/02/pandikar-amin-heads-ft-day-awards-282-conferred/|date=2 February 2009|accessdate=14 September 2018|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|title=Pandikar Amin heads FT Day awards, 282 conferred|work=[[Bernama]]}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Penang}} :\n** [[File:MY-PEN Order of the Defender of State - Knight Grand Commander - DUPN.svg|50px]] Knight Grand Commander of the [[List of post-nominal letters (Penang)|Order of the Defender of State]] (DUPN) - '''Datuk Seri Utama''' (2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2013/08/26/pandikar-amin-heads-honour-roll-speaker-among-1085-to-be-conferred-awards/|date=26 August 2013|accessdate=14 September 2018|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|title=Pandikar Amin heads honour roll|work=Winnie Yeoh and Derrick Vinesh}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Sabah}} :\n** [[File:MY-SAB Order of Kinabalu - PGDK.svg|50px]] Commander of the [[Order of Kinabalu]] (PGDK) - '''Datuk''' (1994)\n** [[File:MY-SAB Order of Kinabalu - SPDK.svg|50px]] Grand Commander of the [[Order of Kinabalu]] (SPDK) - '''Datuk Seri Panglima''' (2010)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/10/03/dpm-heads-sabah-tyt-honours-list/|date=3 October 2010|accessdate=14 September 2018|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|title=DPM heads Sabah TYT honours list|work=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ramli Ngah Talib]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat]]|years=2008 \u2013 2018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mohamad Ariff Md Yusof|Mohd Ariff Md Yusof]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Sixth Mahathir cabinet}}\n{{Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat}}\n{{Portal bar|Malaysia|Biography|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mulia, Pandikar Amin}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sabah]]\n[[Category:Bajau people]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Malaysian lawyers]]\n[[Category:United Sabah National Organisation politicians]]\n[[Category:United Malays National Organisation politicians]]\n[[Category:Angkatan Keadilan Rakyat politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Negara]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Sabah State Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Sabah State Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Wolverhampton]]\n[[Category:Members of Lincoln's Inn]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Kinabalu]]\n[[Category:Grand Commanders of the Order of Kinabalu]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Loyalty to the Crown of 