ajuddin of Perlis|Sirajuddin]]\n| constituency2 = ''Senator''\n\n| constituency_AM3 = [[Tempasuk (state constituency)|Tempasuk]]\n| assembly3 = Sabah State Legislative\n| term_start3 = 2004\n| term_end3 = 2008\n| predecessor3 = Musbah Jamli\n| successor3 = Musbah Jamli\n\n| constituency_AM4 = [[Usukan (state constituency)|Usukan]]\n| assembly4 = Sabah State Legislative\n| term_start4 = 1982\n| term_end4 = 1985\n| predecessor4 = [[Mohamed Said Keruak]]\n| successor4 = [[Mustapha Harun]]\n\n| office5          = President of [[People's Justice Front]] (AKAR)\n| term_start5      = 1989\n| term_end5        = 1995\n| predecessor5     = ''Inaugural holder''\n| successor5       = ''Post abolished''\n\n| citizenship      = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| party            = [[Independent politician|Independent]] (2019-)<br />[[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO) (2001-2018)<br />[[People's Justice Front]] (AKAR) (1989-2001)<br />[[United Sabah National Organisation]] (USNO) (1986-1989)\n| otherparty       = [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) (1986-2018)\n| occupation       = [[Politician]]\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Wolverhampton]]<br />[[Lincoln's Inn]]\n| relations        =\n| spouse           = Hadijah Abdullah Teng\n| children         =\n| website          =\n| footnotes        =\n}}\n\n[[Malay titles#Tan Sri|Tan Sri]] [[Malay titles#Datuk Seri|Datuk Seri Panglima]] '''Pandikar Amin bin Mulia''' ([[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u06a4\u0646\u062f\u0643\u0627\u0631 \u0623\u0645\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u0644\u064a\u0627; born 17 September 1955) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician. He was the [[Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat|Speaker]] of the [[Dewan Rakyat]], the lower house of the [[Parliament of Malaysia]] from April 2008 to May 2018. Presently he is an [[independent politician]].\n\n== Early background ==\nPandikar Amin was born in a poor family in a remote village in [[Kota Belud]], [[Sabah]]. Prior to going to [[England]] for tertiary education, he received education at [[Maktab Sabah, Kota Kinabalu|Sabah College]] in [[Kota Kinabalu]]. He was a graduate of [[University of Wolverhampton|Wolverhampton Polytechnic]] and [[Lincoln's Inn]].\n\n== Political career ==\n=== Pre-speakership ===\nPandikar Amin entered politics in 1982 as a member of [[United Sabah National Organisation]] (USNO) and later picked as the [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) parliamentary candidate for [[Kota Belud (federal constituency)|Kota Belud]] in [[1982 Malaysian general election|1982 general elections]] but lost to the Independent candidate. At the age of 27, however he became [[Sabah State Legislative Assembly|Sabah state assemblyman]] for [[Usukan (state constituency)|Usukan]] from 1982 to 1985. He was appointed the Speaker of [[Sabah State Legislative Assembly]] from 1986 to 1988.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2008/5/1/parliament/21119683&sec=parliament|title=Baptism of fire for Speaker Pandikar Amin at first sitting|date=1 May 2008|work=The Star|accessdate=1 May 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501130318/http://www.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2008%2F5%2F1%2Fparliament%2F21119683&sec=parliament|archivedate=1 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, he was appointed as a [[Dewan Negara|Senator]] and Minister in the [[Prime Minister's Department (Malaysia)|Prime Minister's Department]] until 2002. He was president of [[People's Justice Front]] (AKAR), one of the BN component parties in [[Sabah]], at that time. He was elected again Sabah assemblyman from 2004 to 2008; for [[Tempasuk (state constituency)|Tempasuk]].\n\n=== Speakership in the Dewan Rakyat ===\nAfter the [[2008 Malaysian general election|2008 general elections]], the BN coalition government announced that Pandikar, a member of the [[United Malays National Organisation]] (UMNO), would be the new Speaker, replacing [[Ramli Ngah Talib]].<ref>{{cite news| title=MPs urged to follow the rules| date=26 April 2008| url=http://themalaysianinsider.com/mni/mps-urged-to-follow-the-rules.html| work=The Malaysian Insider| accessdate=27 April 2008| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717012931/http://themalaysianinsider.com/mni/mps-urged-to-follow-the-rules.html| archivedate=17 July 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe 12th Parliament was the first to be presided over entirely by East Malaysians; Pandikar and his deputies, [[Wan Junaidi Tuanku Jaafar]] and [[Ronald Kiandee]], hail from either [[Sabah]] or [[Sarawak]].<ref>{{cite news | first=V. | last=Vasudevan | author2= | title=A day of firsts in parliament | date=28 April 2008 | publisher= | url =http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Monday/National/2225389/Article/index_html | work =[[New Straits Times]] | pages = | accessdate = 28 April 2008 | language = |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080501173244/http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Monday/National/2225389/Article/index_html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 1 May 2008}}</ref> In mid-May, after Parliament convened, Pandikar resigned as Kota Marudu UMNO division chief, citing the need to be a neutral presiding officer. He denied his resignation was linked to possible party-switching amongst UMNO MPs from East Malaysia.<ref>{{cite news | title=Pandikar Amin quits as Kota Marudu Umno chief | date=16 May 2008 | publisher= | url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2008/05/16/pandikar-amin-quits-as-kota-marudu-umno-chief/ | work=[[The Star Online]] | accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nAhead of the [[2018 Malaysian general election|2018 general elections]], Pandikar announced his intention to contest, thus returning to active politics after serving as Parliamentary Speaker for two terms.<ref>{{cite news | first=Clarence | last=Dol | title=Pandikar returning to politics | date=5 April 2017 | url=http://dailyexpress.com.my/news.cfm?NewsID=116899 | work=Daily Express | accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref> Somehow he was not pick as candidate to contest the elections that saw the downfall of BN in both the federal and state governments. Amidst his appointment to the UMNO's supreme council in 14 July 2018; he quitted on 12 December 2018 along with other Sabah UMNO assemblyman to be independents.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2018/12/13/umno-sabah-ship-sinking/|title=Umno Sabah ship sinking|author=NEIL BRIAN JOSEPH|publisher=[[The Borneo Post]]|date=13 December 2018|accessdate=13 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* {{Flag|Malaysia}} :\n** [[File:Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia - SSM.svg|50px]] Companion of the [[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia#Companion|Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia]] (JSM) (1993)\n** [[File:Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia - PSM.svg|50px]] Commander of the [[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia#Commander|Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia]] (PSM) - '''Tan Sri''' (2002)<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.istiadat.gov.my/index.php/component/semakanlantikanskp/|title=Semakan Penerima Darjah Kebesaran, Bintang dan Pingat}}</ref>\n\n* {{Flag|Federal Territory (Malaysia)}} :\n** [[File:MY-FED Darjah Mahkota Wilayah - Grand Knight - SUMW.svg|50px]] Grand Knight of the [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the Malaysian states and federal territories#Federal Territories|Order of the Territorial Crown]] (SUMW) - '''Datuk Seri Utama''' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2009/02/02/pandikar-amin-heads-ft-day-awards-282-conferred/|date=2 February 2009|accessdate=14 September 2018|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|title=Pandikar Amin heads FT Day awards, 282 conferred|work=[[Bernama]]}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Penang}} :\n** [[File:MY-PEN Order of the Defender of State - Knight Grand Commander - DUPN.svg|50px]] Knight Grand Commander of the [[List of post-nominal letters (Penang)|Order of the Defender of State]] (DUPN) - '''Datuk Seri Utama''' (2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2013/08/26/pandikar-amin-heads-honour-roll-speaker-among-1085-to-be-conferred-awards/|date=26 August 2013|accessdate=14 September 2018|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|title=Pandikar Amin heads honour roll|work=Winnie Yeoh and Derrick Vinesh}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Sabah}} :\n** [[File:MY-SAB Order of Kinabalu - PGDK.svg|50px]] Commander of the [[Order of Kinabalu]] (PGDK) - '''Datuk''' (1994)\n** [[File:MY-SAB Order of Kinabalu - SPDK.svg|50px]] Grand Commander of the [[Order of Kinabalu]] (SPDK) - '''Datuk Seri Panglima''' (2010)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/10/03/dpm-heads-sabah-tyt-honours-list/|date=3 October 2010|accessdate=14 September 2018|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|title=DPM heads Sabah TYT honours list|work=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ramli Ngah Talib]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat]]|years=2008 \u2013 2018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mohamad Ariff Md Yusof|Mohd Ariff Md Yusof]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Sixth Mahathir cabinet}}\n{{Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat}}\n{{Portal bar|Malaysia|Biography|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mulia, Pandikar Amin}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sabah]]\n[[Category:Bajau people]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Malaysian lawyers]]\n[[Category:United Sabah National Organisation politicians]]\n[[Category:United Malays National Organisation politicians]]\n[[Category:Angkatan Keadilan Rakyat politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Negara]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Sabah State Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Sabah State Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Wolverhampton]]\n[[Category:Members of Lincoln's Inn]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Kinabalu]]\n[[Category:Grand Commanders of the Order of Kinabalu]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian people]]\n\n{{Malaysia-politician-stub}}\n{{malaysia-bio-stub}}\n{{politics-stub}}\n{{malaysia-stub}}\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "stub sorting, removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pandikar_Amin_Mulia"}
{"title_page": "Mohamad Ariff Md Yusof", "text_new": "{{short description|Speaker of the House of Representatives of Malaysia}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2018}}{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Malay name|Mohamad Ariff|Md Yusof}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific_prefix= [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Tan Sri|Tan Sri]] [[Malay titles#State titles|Dato']]\n|name=Mohamad Ariff Md Yusof\n|native_name=\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0639\u0627\u0631\u0641 \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062f \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641\n|honorific-suffix = {{small|[[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia#Commander|PSM]] [[Order of Loyalty to the Royal House of Kedah|DSDK]]}}\n|image= \n|caption=\n\n|office=9th [[Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n|monarch=[[Muhammad V of Kelantan|Muhammad V]] <br /> [[Abdullah of Pahang|Abdullah]]\n|primeminister   = [[Mahathir Mohamed]]\n|deputy=[[Mohd Rashid Hasnon]] <br /> [[Nga Kor Ming]]\n|appointer=\n|nominator=\n|term_start=16 July 2018\n|term_end= \n|predecessor=[[Pandikar Amin Mulia]]\n|successor=\n|constituency = ''non-MP'' ([[Independent politician|Independent]])\n\n|birth_name = Mohamad Ariff bin Md Yusof\n|birth_date = {{birth year and age|1949|}}\n|birth_place = [[Sungai Petani]], [[Kedah]], [[Federation of Malaya]] (now [[Malaysia]])\n|death_date = \n|death_place = \n|citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n|nationality = {{MAS}}\n|party = [[Independent politician|Independent]] {{small|(2018-present)}}<br />[[National Trust Party (Malaysia)|AMANAH]] {{small|(2015-2018)}}<br />[[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]] {{small|(until 2015)}}\n|spouse = Hakimah Hassan\n|children = Muhamad Lutfi (Press secretary to the [[Minister of Finance (Malaysia)|FM]] - [[Lim Guan Eng]])\n|education = [[Royal Military College (Malaysia)|Royal Military College]]\n|alma_mater = [[London School of Economics]]<br />[[Lincoln's Inn]]\n|website = \n|footnotes = \n}}\n\n[[Malay titles#Tan Sri|Tan Sri]] [[Malay titles#State titles|Dato']] '''Mohamad Ariff bin Md Yusof''' ([[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0639\u0627\u0631\u0641 \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062f \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641; born 1949) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician who is the current [[Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat]], the lower house of the [[Parliament of Malaysia]] since 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2018/07/357971/mohamad-ariff-speaker-dewan-rakyat-pm|title=Mohamad Ariff speaker Dewan Rakyat - PM|date=2018-07-15|work=HM Online|access-date=2018-07-15|language=ms|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715151954/https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2018/07/357971/mohamad-ariff-speaker-dewan-rakyat-pm|archive-date=15 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Presently he is an [[independent politician]].<ref name=independence.speaker>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/15/mohamad-ariff-best-fits-the-bill-he-is-well-known-for-being-fair-and-independentminded-says-law-expe/|title=Mohamad Ariff best fits the bill|work= [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|author= Razak Ahmad|date=15 July 2018|access-date=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMohamad Ariff was born in [[Sungai Petani]], [[Kedah]] in 1949. He graduated from the [[London School of Economics]] (LSE) with a Bachelor's degree in law.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Career ==\nMohamad Ariff joined the Faculty of Law in [[University of Malaya]] once he graduated from LSE. In 1986, he became an advocate and a solicitor at his own legal practice called Cheang & Ariff.\n\nMohamad Ariff joined the [[Securities Commission Malaysia]] (SC) and became the first Market Supervision Department Director from 1993 to 1995. From 1995 to 1996, he served as a Director of Kuala Lumpur Options and Super Exchange (KLOSE). He served as a member of the advisory board of Company's Commission of Malaysia from 2007 to 2008. He also was a member of the Rating Review Committee and Malaysian Rating Agency until 2008.\n\nMohamad Ariff was appointed a Judicial Commissioner for the [[High Court of Malaya]] in 2008. He was made a full judge of the same in 2009. In 2012, he was elevated to the [[Court of Appeal of Malaysia|Court of Appeal]]. He retired from the [[Judiciary of Malaysia|Malaysian Judiciary]] in 2015 and returned to his prior legal practice, Cheang & Ariff.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/s/1652513/who-is-ariff-yusof-pakatans-choice-for-dewan-rakyat-speaker|title=Who is Ariff Yusof, Pakatan's choice for Dewan Rakyat Speaker? {{!}} Malay Mail|access-date=2018-07-15|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715100406/https://www.malaymail.com/s/1652513/who-is-ariff-yusof-pakatans-choice-for-dewan-rakyat-speaker|archive-date=15 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nMohamad Ariff was a high court judge during the [[2009 Perak constitutional crisis]]. He also served as the judge removing the Home Ministry's ban on the book authored by the [[Sisters in Islam]] (SIS) entitled Muslim Women and the Challenges of Islamic Extremism.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Muslim women and the challenge of Islamic extremism|date=2005|publisher=Sisters in Islam|others=Norani Othman., SIS Forum (Malaysia) Berhad.|isbn=9832622247|location=Petaling Jaya, Selangor, Malaysia|oclc=68965854}}</ref> As a Court of Appeal Judge, he led a panel of judges in the case of [[Teoh Beng Hock]], a man killed while in the custody of the [[Malaysian Anti-Corruption Commission]] (MACC).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-politik/speaker-dewan-rakyat-ke-9-berpengalaman-luas-dalam-undang-undang-180534|title=Speaker Dewan Rakyat ke-9 berpengalaman luas dalam undang-undang {{!}} Astro Awani|website=www.astroawani.com|language=ms|access-date=2018-07-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715152055/http://www.astroawani.com/berita-politik/speaker-dewan-rakyat-ke-9-berpengalaman-luas-dalam-undang-undang-180534|archive-date=15 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/01/25/ban-lifted-on-sisters-in-islam-book-updated/|title=Ban lifted on Sisters in Islam book (Updated) - Nation {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2018-07-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716165554/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/01/25/ban-lifted-on-sisters-in-islam-book-updated/|archive-date=16 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nMohamad Ariff was a member and candidate of the [[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party]] (PAS) for {{nseat|Kota Damansara}}, Selangor in [[Malaysian General Election, 2004|2004 general election]] but failed to win.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://m.utusan.com.my/berita/politik/pilihan-raya/pilihan-raya-umum-ke-14/maklumat-calon-dan-kawasan-pilihan-raya-n39-kota-damansara-selangor-1.652638 |title=Archived copy |access-date=16 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716112041/http://m.utusan.com.my/berita/politik/pilihan-raya/pilihan-raya-umum-ke-14/maklumat-calon-dan-kawasan-pilihan-raya-n39-kota-damansara-selangor-1.652638 |archive-date=16 July 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Then he joined [[National Trust Party (Malaysia)|Parti Amanah Negara]] (AMANAH), a component party of [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) coalition in 2015.<ref name=\":0\" /> He resigned all of his party posts and became an [[independent politician]] on 1 July 2018 in order to become the PH coalition's candidate for the speakership.<ref name=independence.speaker/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/434397|title=Speaker letak jawatan dalam parti pada 1 Julai|date=2018-07-16|work=Malaysiakini|access-date=2018-07-16|language=ms-MY|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716165549/https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/434397|archive-date=16 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]''': N39 [[Kota Damansara (state constituency)|Kota Damansara]] (P107 Subang)<ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=4 February 2017 }} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{Cite web\n  | title = Malaysia General Election \n  | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data\n  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]\n  | url = http://undi.info/#\n  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref> \n!|Year\n!colspan=2|Government \n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|[[2004 Malaysian general election|2004]]\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|Mohamad Ariff Md Yusof ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" |4,827 \n|27.19%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Mohd Mokhtar Ahmad Dahlan''' ([[United Malays National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''12,926''' \n|'''72.81%'''\n|18,697\n|8,099\n|77.84%\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n* {{Flag|Malaysia}} :\n** [[File:Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia - PSM.svg|50px]] Commander of the [[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia#Commander|Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia]] (PSM) - '''Tan Sri''' (2019)<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=9 September 2019|date=9 September 2019|publisher=[[Malay Mail]]|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/09/09/cj-ag-tommy-thomas-igp-among-those-awarded-tan-sri-in-conjunction-with-agon/1788751|title=CJ, AG Tommy Thomas, IGP among those awarded 'Tan Sri' in conjunction with Agong's birthday|work=[[Bernama]]}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Kedah}} :\n** [[File:MY-KED Order of Loyalty to the Royal House of Kedah - Knight Companion (DSDK).svg|50px]] Knight Companion of the [[Order of Loyalty to the Royal House of Kedah]] (DSDK) - '''Dato'''' (2012)<ref>[http://www.istiadat.gov.my/v1/images/2012.pdf Senarai penerima Darjah Kebesaran Kedah 2012]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n\n==References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Pandikar Amin Mulia]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat]]|years= 2018-present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat}}\n{{Portal bar|Malaysia|Biography|Law|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Md Yusof, Mohamad Ariff}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kedah]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Malay descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Malaysian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Malaysian judges]]\n[[Category:Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Parti Amanah Negara politicians]]\n[[Category:Independent politicians in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n[[Category:Members of Lincoln's Inn]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:21st-century Malaysian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Speaker of the House of Representatives of Malaysia}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2018}}{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Malay name|Mohamad Ariff|Md Yusof}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific_prefix= [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Tan Sri|Tan Sri]] [[Malay titles#State titles|Dato']]\n|name=Mohamad Ariff Md Yusof\n|native_name=\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0639\u0627\u0631\u0641 \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062f \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641\n|honorific-suffix = {{small|[[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia#Commander|PSM]] [[Order of Loyalty to the Royal House of Kedah|DSDK]]}}\n|image= \n|caption=\n\n|office=9th [[Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n|monarch=[[Muhammad V of Kelantan|Muhammad V]] <br /> [[Abdullah of Pahang|Abdullah]]\n|primeminister   = [[Mahathir Mohamed]]\n|deputy=[[Mohd Rashid Hasnon]] <br /> [[Nga Kor Ming]]\n|appointer=\n|nominator=\n|term_start=16 July 2018\n|term_end= \n|predecessor=[[Pandikar Amin Mulia]]\n|successor=\n|constituency = ''non-MP'' ([[Independent politician|Independent]])\n\n|birth_name = Mohamad Ariff bin Md Yusof\n|birth_date = {{birth year and age|1949|}}\n|birth_place = [[Sungai Petani]], [[Kedah]], [[Federation of Malaya]] (now [[Malaysia]])\n|death_date = \n|death_place = \n|citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n|nationality = {{MAS}}\n|party = [[Independent politician|Independent]] {{small|(2018-present)}}<br />[[National Trust Party (Malaysia)|AMANAH]] {{small|(2015-2018)}}<br />[[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]] {{small|(until 2015)}}\n|spouse = Hakimah Hassan\n|children = Muhamad Lutfi (Press secretary to the [[Minister of Finance (Malaysia)|FM]] - [[Lim Guan Eng]])\n|education = [[Royal Military College (Malaysia)|Royal Military College]]\n|alma_mater = [[London School of Economics]]<br />[[Lincoln's Inn]]\n|website = \n|footnotes = \n}}\n\n[[Malay titles#Tan Sri|Tan Sri]] [[Malay titles#State titles|Dato']] '''Mohamad Ariff bin Md Yusof''' ([[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]: \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0639\u0627\u0631\u0641 \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u062f \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641; born 1949) is a [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] politician who is the current [[Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat]], the lower house of the [[Parliament of Malaysia]] since 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2018/07/357971/mohamad-ariff-speaker-dewan-rakyat-pm|title=Mohamad Ariff speaker Dewan Rakyat - PM|date=2018-07-15|work=HM Online|access-date=2018-07-15|language=ms|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715151954/https://www.hmetro.com.my/mutakhir/2018/07/357971/mohamad-ariff-speaker-dewan-rakyat-pm|archive-date=15 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Presently he is an [[independent politician]].<ref name=independence.speaker>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/15/mohamad-ariff-best-fits-the-bill-he-is-well-known-for-being-fair-and-independentminded-says-law-expe/|title=Mohamad Ariff best fits the bill|work= [[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|author= Razak Ahmad|date=15 July 2018|access-date=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMohamad Ariff was born in [[Sungai Petani]], [[Kedah]] in 1949. He graduated from the [[London School of Economics]] (LSE) with a Bachelor's degree in law.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Career ==\nMohamad Ariff joined the Faculty of Law in [[University of Malaya]] once he graduated from LSE. In 1986, he became an advocate and a solicitor at his own legal practice called Cheang & Ariff.\n\nMohamad Ariff joined the [[Securities Commission Malaysia]] (SC) and became the first Market Supervision Department Director from 1993 to 1995. From 1995 to 1996, he served as a Director of Kuala Lumpur Options and Super Exchange (KLOSE). He served as a member of the advisory board of Company's Commission of Malaysia from 2007 to 2008. He also was a member of the Rating Review Committee and Malaysian Rating Agency until 2008.\n\nMohamad Ariff was appointed a Judicial Commissioner for the [[High Court of Malaya]] in 2008. He was made a full judge of the same in 2009. In 2012, he was elevated to the [[Court of Appeal of Malaysia|Court of Appeal]]. He retired from the [[Judiciary of Malaysia|Malaysian Judiciary]] in 2015 and returned to his prior legal practice, Cheang & Ariff.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/s/1652513/who-is-ariff-yusof-pakatans-choice-for-dewan-rakyat-speaker|title=Who is Ariff Yusof, Pakatan's choice for Dewan Rakyat Speaker? {{!}} Malay Mail|access-date=2018-07-15|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715100406/https://www.malaymail.com/s/1652513/who-is-ariff-yusof-pakatans-choice-for-dewan-rakyat-speaker|archive-date=15 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nMohamad Ariff was a high court judge during the [[2009 Perak constitutional crisis]]. He also served as the judge removing the Home Ministry's ban on the book authored by the [[Sisters in Islam]] (SIS) entitled Muslim Women and the Challenges of Islamic Extremism.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Muslim women and the challenge of Islamic extremism|date=2005|publisher=Sisters in Islam|others=Norani Othman., SIS Forum (Malaysia) Berhad.|isbn=9832622247|location=Petaling Jaya, Selangor, Malaysia|oclc=68965854}}</ref> As a Court of Appeal Judge, he led a panel of judges in the case of [[Teoh Beng Hock]], a man killed while in the custody of the [[Malaysian Anti-Corruption Commission]] (MACC).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-politik/speaker-dewan-rakyat-ke-9-berpengalaman-luas-dalam-undang-undang-180534|title=Speaker Dewan Rakyat ke-9 berpengalaman luas dalam undang-undang {{!}} Astro Awani|website=www.astroawani.com|language=ms|access-date=2018-07-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715152055/http://www.astroawani.com/berita-politik/speaker-dewan-rakyat-ke-9-berpengalaman-luas-dalam-undang-undang-180534|archive-date=15 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/01/25/ban-lifted-on-sisters-in-islam-book-updated/|title=Ban lifted on Sisters in Islam book (Updated) - Nation {{!}} The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my|access-date=2018-07-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716165554/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2010/01/25/ban-lifted-on-sisters-in-islam-book-updated/|archive-date=16 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nMohamad Ariff was a member and candidate of the [[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party]] (PAS) for {{nseat|Kota Damansara}}, Selangor in [[Malaysian General Election, 2004|2004 general election]] but failed to win.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://m.utusan.com.my/berita/politik/pilihan-raya/pilihan-raya-umum-ke-14/maklumat-calon-dan-kawasan-pilihan-raya-n39-kota-damansara-selangor-1.652638 |title=Archived copy |access-date=16 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716112041/http://m.utusan.com.my/berita/politik/pilihan-raya/pilihan-raya-umum-ke-14/maklumat-calon-dan-kawasan-pilihan-raya-n39-kota-damansara-selangor-1.652638 |archive-date=16 July 2018 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Then he joined [[National Trust Party (Malaysia)|Parti Amanah Negara]] (AMANAH), a component party of [[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) coalition in 2015.<ref name=\":0\" /> He resigned all of his party posts and became an [[independent politician]] on 1 July 2018 in order to become the PH coalition's candidate for the speakership.<ref name=independence.speaker/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/434397|title=Speaker letak jawatan dalam parti pada 1 Julai|date=2018-07-16|work=Malaysiakini|access-date=2018-07-16|language=ms-MY|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180716165549/https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/434397|archive-date=16 July 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Selangor State Legislative Assembly]]''': N39 [[Kota Damansara (state constituency)|Kota Damansara]] (P107 Subang)<ref name=\"election results\">{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php |title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri |publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]] |language=Malay |accessdate=4 February 2017 }} Percentage figures based on total turnout.</ref><ref name=\"undiinfo\">{{Cite web\n  | title = Malaysia General Election \n  | work = undiinfo Malaysian Election Data\n  | publisher = [[Malaysiakini]]\n  | url = http://undi.info/#\n  | accessdate = 4 February 2017}} Results only available from the [[2004 Malaysian general election|2004 election]].</ref> \n!|Year\n!colspan=2|Government \n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opposition\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!|Ballots cast\n!|Majority\n!|Turnout\n|-\n|[[2004 Malaysian general election|2004]]\n|{{Party shading/PAS}} |\n|Mohamad Ariff Md Yusof ([[Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party|PAS]])\n|align=\"right\" |4,827 \n|27.19%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Mohd Mokhtar Ahmad Dahlan''' ([[United Malays National Organisation|'''UMNO''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''12,926''' \n|'''72.81%'''\n|18,697\n|8,099\n|77.84%\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n* {{Flag|Malaysia}} :\n** [[File:Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia - PSM.svg|50px]] Commander of the [[Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia#Commander|Order of Loyalty to the Crown of Malaysia]] (PSM) - '''Tan Sri''' (2019)<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=9 September 2019|date=9 September 2019|publisher=[[Malay Mail]]|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2019/09/09/cj-ag-tommy-thomas-igp-among-those-awarded-tan-sri-in-conjunction-with-agon/1788751|title=CJ, AG Tommy Thomas, IGP among those awarded 'Tan Sri' in conjunction with Agong's birthday|work=[[Bernama]]}}</ref>\n\n* {{Flag|Kedah}} :\n** [[File:MY-KED Order of Loyalty to the Royal House of Kedah - Knight Companion (DSDK).svg|50px]] Knight Companion of the [[Order of Loyalty to the Royal House of Kedah]] (DSDK) - '''Dato'''' (2012)<ref>[http://www.istiadat.gov.my/v1/images/2012.pdf Senarai penerima Darjah Kebesaran Kedah 2012]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n\n==References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Pandikar Amin Mulia]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat]]|years= 2018-present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Speaker of the Dewan Rakyat}}\n{{Portal bar|Malaysia|Biography|Law|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Md Yusof, Mohamad Ariff}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kedah]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Malay descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Malaysian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Malaysian judges]]\n[[Category:Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Parti 